Introduction to Databases

12 steps

Throughout our exploration, we have delved deep into the realm of back-end development, discovering that it encompasses more than just the creation of visually stunning front ends or the handling of incoming requests. An integral part of back-end development revolves around databasing.

Think of a database as the digital reservoir for developers a sophisticated storage solution embedded within the heart of your web ecosystem. Unlike standard web storage, databases are robust and persistent, offering the capacity to house substantial volumes of data in an organized and structured manner. The objectives of a database are multifaceted: it must seamlessly accommodate vast information stores, enable efficient data retrieval via unique identifiers, and execute a spectrum of database operations.

Our application's interaction with databases takes center stage. The Back End serves as the middleman through which data is transferred to and fetched from the database, allowing a seamless flow of information. In software development, there are two prominent types of databases emerging: Relational Databases, characterized by Structured Query Language (SQL), and Non-Relational Databases, often referred to as NoSQL databases. We will dive deeper into databases.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

JavaScript Basics and Intermediate

Learning Outcomes

Upon completing your learning, you will be able to

  • Describe the core concepts of databases, their role in storing and managing data, and the essential features they offer for effective data manipulation.
  • Explore the realm of NoSQL databases, understand their advantages, and create your own database with MongoDB Atlas
  • Establish seamless connections between your NodeJS Back End application and databases, enabling data transfer and retrieval.
  • Design efficient data models and schemas that cater to the unique requirements of the project.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 12

  • Step 1: Setting Up Our Workspace

    Now, go ahead and open your coding workspace of your choice. Open your terminal in your code editor and ensure that the current working directory is the root folder, StackUp-BackEnd-ExpressJS.

    Next, enter the following commands in your terminal.

    mkdir Introduction-to-Databases
cd Introduction-to-Databases
npm install express morgan body-parser dotenv mongodb mongoose ejs

    In the code above, there are 3 commands. First, using mkdir, it creates a new folder. The next command will change the current working directory to the new folder we have created. Lastly, the last command will install the following 7 packages: Express, Morgan, Body Parser, DotEnv, MongoDB, Mongoose and EJS. 

  • Step 2: Project Setup

    Before we continue, let us create the folders and files we need for this project. Within your project folder, i.e. Introduction-to-Databases, we are going to create a new folder called models. It will be the folder that will store the schemas of our database. For this project, we will be using a Non-Relational Database called MongoDB. It is a NoSQL Database.

    Next, in the same project folder, create a folder called views and another folder called public. These folders are for the EJS files that we will be creating in later steps. The public folder will contain all the files needed that are publicly accessible by the users of the web application. The views folder will contain the EJS files that will be server-rendered to the Front End.

    By now, if you have done the workspace and project setup correctly, your project folder Introduction-to-Databases should have four folders - models, node_modules, public, and views, and two JSON files - package-lock.json and package.json.

  • Step 3: Environment Variables

    Next, within the project folder, Introduction-to-Databases, create a new file called .env. This file will be where we can store sensitive information like API Keys, Application Secrets, Database connections and more. It is a recommended practice for developers to adhere to this convention as .env files are usually used on a local level. Though the credentials and information are stored in plain text, usually .env files will be ignored by Git and will not be stored in a version source control service (VCS) like GitHub or GitLab. This reduces the risk of you having sensitive information uploaded onto a public GitHub repository.

    Now, copy the code below and add it to the .env file.

    db_connection="to_be_added_in_subsequent_steps"
PORT=3000
    Plain text

    In the code above, we have defined our port number to be 3000. Port numbers can be any number within the range of 1 to 65535. Only one application can use a specific port at any point in time. As long as the port is free, your NodeJS application is able to use it and listen for any incoming requests. However, there are some restrictions and conventions you will need to adhere to. Just to name a few, ports 80 and 443 are reserved for HTTP requests, port 22 is for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections and port 21 is for File Transfer Protocol (FTP). If you are interested in learning more about the various port reservations, you may read more about it here.

    For this quest, we will be using the .env file to store our application port number and our Database connection string. You can think of this file as an Environment Configuration. In Software Development, when deploying our applications to servers, sometimes our application might change different variables that run the application, like different database credentials, port numbers and more. .env files will be applied locally on the device where the file is placed.

    Next, you might be wondering how we are going to use these variables in our JavaScript files. In Step 1, we installed a package called dotenv. It is a JavaScript package that will do the necessary heavy lifting in managing and storing these variables, making it accessible to us in the JavaScript files.

    require('dotenv').config();



const server = app.listen(process.env.PORT, () => {
  console.log("Server listening");
  mongoose.connect(process.env.db_connection).then(() => {
    console.log("Database Connected");
  });
});

    The code above is a sample usage of how we can use the environment variables. Firstly, we will need to import the dotenv package and once we are done with that, we will be able to access these variables by using process.env.name of variable. The name of the variable is case-sensitive, and it will be the same as the variables in the .env file. 

  • Step 4: Views and EJS

    We will be creating a single-page web application using EJS as the View Engine. EJS is Embedded JavaScript and it will be a way for us to create a templated front-end view using HTML and CSS as the foundation. We are able to dynamically import and change the content shown within the EJS views as well.

    Within the views folder, create a new file called index.ejs. Within this file, add the following code:

    <!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
    <title>To Do App</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css">
</head>

<body>
    <h1>To-Do App</h1>
    <form action="/tasks/" method="post">
        <input type="text" name="task" id="task" placeholder="Add a new task">
        <button type="submit">Add Task</button>
    </form>
    <ul>
        <% todos.forEach(function(todo) { %>
            <li>
                <form action="/tasks/<%= todo._id %>/update" method="post" style="display: inline;">
                    <input type="text" name="task" id="task" value="<%- todo.task %>" />
                    <button type="submit">Update</button>
                </form>
                <form action="/tasks/<%= todo._id %>/complete" method="post" style="display: inline;">
                    <button type="submit">
                        <%= todo.is_completed ? 'Uncomplete' : 'Complete' %>
                    </button>
                </form>
                <form action="/tasks/<%= todo._id %>/delete" method="post" style="display: inline;">
                    <button type="submit">Delete</button>
                </form>
            </li>
            <% }); %>
    </ul>
</body>

</html>
    HTML

    In this file, the elements are HTML elements. Essentially the view engine will use the templated front-end file, like index.ejs, and during the ingestion, which is a process of taking in the raw EJS file and replacing the variables with HTML elements. Once the ingestion phase is done, it will send the formatted HTML file back to the client.

    In line 16, it is an EJS loop that iterates through each data item (todo) in the array and generates HTML code for each item. The loop uses the % ... % tags to execute JavaScript code within the HTML. Line 24 uses an EJS tag to dynamically generate the button label. If todo.is_completed is true, the label becomes "Uncomplete"; otherwise, it becomes "Complete".

  • Step 6: App.js and Routings

    Now, we will need to create the main entry file for our Back End Application. Within the project folder, Introduction-to-Databases, create a new file called app.js and add the following code: 

    const express = require('express');
require('dotenv').config();
const mongoose = require("mongoose");
const TaskModel = require('./models/TaskModel');
const morgan = require('morgan');

// Create the Express app
const app = express();

// Connect to MongoDB
const server = app.listen(process.env.PORT, () => {
  console.log("Server listening");
  mongoose.connect(process.env.db_connection).then(() => {
    console.log("Database Connected");
  });
});

app.use(express.static('public'));
app.set('view engine', 'ejs');
app.use(morgan('dev'))
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  TaskModel.find({}).then((tasks) => {
    res.render('index.ejs', { todos: tasks });
  })
});

app.post('/tasks/', (req, res) => {
  const newTodo = new TaskModel({
    task: req.body.task
  });

  newTodo.save();
  res.redirect('/');
});

app.post('/tasks/:id/complete', (req, res) => {
  TaskModel.findById(req.params.id).then((todo) => {
    todo.is_completed = !todo.is_completed;
    todo.save();
    res.redirect('/');
  });
});

app.post('/tasks/:id/update', (req, res) => {
  TaskModel.findById(req.params.id).then((todo) => {
    todo.task = req.body.task;
    todo.save();
    res.redirect('/');
  });
});

app.post('/tasks/:id/delete', (req, res) => {
  TaskModel.findByIdAndDelete(req.params.id).then(() => {
    res.redirect('/');
  });
});

module.exports = {
  mongoose,
};
    JavaScript

    You might recall in Step 3 that we used the .env file to store our environment variables. In line 2 of this file, we will import the module to this file. Next in line 13, we have used the environment variable (process.env.db_connection) to connect to our database. We will be using MongoDB. We will touch more on databases in the subsequent steps.

    Referring to lines 11 to 16, we will first connect to our database using our database connection string in our environment variables. Once we have connected to our database, we will start listening to any incoming message to our back-end application. Since we have yet to set up our database, we are unable to connect to the database yet.

    Next from line 18 to line 21, we will apply the various middlewares which are essentially the configurations we need to set up our back end. In line 18, we will set the public folder by referencing the path in relation to app.js. Next in line 19, we will set the current view engine to EJS. Next, we will configure Morgan to print out the request into the terminal using a dev configuration. Lastly, we will define how Express will receive and configure the incoming request, such that we will be able to use JSON to obtain the data we have received from the client.

    From line 23 to line 59, these are our routes. Previously, we touched on the surface of routings. In this case, we will define the various API endpoints of our application. API endpoints are basically URL and URL parameters that the client is able to contact the back end. Think of them as addresses. When creating a URL string, you might want to consider the various requirements.

    - URLs should represent the resource the client is expecting to fetch

    - In an HTML Method (GET, PUT, POST, etc) URL template strings have to be unique

    Instance 1

    In our application, it is important that our endpoints are unique by each HTML method. The code below shows an example of what is an invalid URL.

    // When updating a status
PUT /api/ [update order details]
PUT /api/ [update order status]

    In a particular method, the entire string should be different as ExpressJS will only take the first instance that matches the incoming request. The next example will show the correct way to create an endpoint.

    PUT /api/orders/details [update order details]
PUT /api/orders/status [update order status]

    Notice how the strings are different and this will not lead to any conflict. 

    Instance 2

    The following example is to show how we can have similar URL strings across the various methods. 

    GET       /api/blogs/ [fetch the updated blogs]
POST     /api/blogs/ [submit a new blog]
PUT        /api/blogs/:blog_id [update a blog by ID]
GET        /api/blogs/:blog_id [fetch a blog by ID]
DELETE  /api/blogs/:blog_id [delete a blog by ID]

    Above is an acceptable manner of how you can organise your routes. Even though the first and second lines above share the same URL string, the methods are different. The same goes for the last 3 endpoints in the example above. 

    Important!

    In ExpressJS routings, to specify that a URL contains a dynamic parameter, you will need to put a colon (:) before the name of the dynamic URL variable. You may refer to Instance 2 in the example above where there is a colon (:) before the variable blog_id. This can be seen in lines 38, 46 and line 54 in app.js. Next, when you want to access the value within the dynamic URL parameter, you can do so using the code below. 

    let blog_id = req.params.blog_id

OR 

let {blog_id} = req.params

    This can be seen in lines 39, 47, and line 55 of app.js. In the code example above, req.params is an object and using object destructuring, we are able to use shorthand as shown in the alternative method in the code example above.

    Do note that HTML form data does not support any other HTML methods except for GET and POST requests. As such, we are only able to use app.get (see line 23) and app.post (see lines 29, 38 and 46) in our ExpressJS app. If we are using the native JavaScript fetch() module, we are able to use other HTML methods like PUT, DELETE and PATCH. Front End Framework like ReactJS and NextJS will have fetch() preinstalled.

  • Step 7: Models and Database

    We are also going to learn how we can store data in our databases. We will use MongoDB which stores their data in JSON documents in an unstructured manner. Each new data is called a document. The documents are stored in a collection. Even though NoSQL databases are unstructured, we are able to provide structure templating to our MongoDB by specifying the schema. Now, within the models folder, create a new file called TaskModel.js and add the code shown below. 

    const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const taskSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  task: {
    type: String,
    required: true,
  },
  is_completed: {
    type: Boolean,
    required: false,
    default: false,
  },
}, {
  timestamps: true,
});

const TaskModel = mongoose.model('tasks', taskSchema);

module.exports = TaskModel;
    JavaScript

    In the code sample above, we will import mongoose, which is an Object Relational Mapping (ORM) module to communicate directly to our database. There are alternatives to communicating with databases. These can come in the form of raw query strings like SELECT * FROM tasks . This is a query string for SQL databases. This includes MySQL and MongoDB.

    The reason why ORMs are better than writing query strings is that they are safer and a recommended practice in software development. Writing raw query strings poses a security concern and a huge risk to SQL injection. SQL injection is the name of a process when someone tries to inject another SQL string with the intent to steal or destroy databases and collections. Gone are the days when we will need to learn Query Languages. But it is still important that we learn the foundations of query strings as a programmer. If you are interested in reading more about SQL injection, please read this article.

    In TaskModel.js, we will define the keys that we are expecting to store in the database. Keys such as task (line 4) and is_completed (line 8). We can also define the data type we are expecting to store within the database (lines 5 and line 9). Lastly, we can also configure whether this key is necessary when creating a new document. If the key is not found within the document creation operation, the process of creating a new document will fail. It is similar to how MySQL checks for non-null values in the columns. In line 17, we will define the name of the collection that will be storing our documents. For this step, we will be using tasks as the name of our collection. In line 14, we will also configure that we would want to track the timestamp. As such we set the timestamp to be true. By doing so, MongoDB will automatically store the timestamp when the document has been created and when the document has been updated.

  • Step 10: App.js and Running Our Code

    GET /

    In your code editor, open app.js and refer to line 24. TaskModel is the same schema that we have created in Step 7. We already imported the file earlier in line 4 of App.js. In line 24, the API that we have created is to fetch all the task documents that are stored within the database. Once we have obtained the documents from the collection, we will parse the tasks into the render in line 25. From there, we will render the Front End with EJS and send the rendered file back to the Front End.

    POST /tasks/

    In this API, we are going to get the task that the user has sent to the Back End Application and store it within the database. In line 30, we will create a new Instance of TaskModel and parse the task that we have received from the Front End. We can obtain the value from the Front End using the req.body.task, which is an object. task is the only compulsory field we need in order to create a new document in the tasks collection. Next in line 34, we will need to commit the new document by using the .save() method and redirect back to the GET / API in line 35.

    POST /tasks/:id/complete

    This API will grab the id as stated within the URL parameter and index the collection by its ID and update the value within the collection. We can do so by using the .findById() method. The method will return the data value that is obtained from the collection. We can simply change the is_completed value by using the exclamation mark (!) to reverse the Boolean value.

    Using the .save() method (line 41), we are able to commit the changes to the database and redirect to GET / in line 42.

    POST /tasks/:id/update

    This API will update the specified task id parsed into the parameter and index the collection by its ID to update the task name. We can do so by obtaining the task from the front end by using the req.body.task in line 48. We will use the same .save() method and commit the changes to the database (line 49) and redirect the user to GET / in line 50.

    POST /tasks/:id/delete

    Lastly, this API will attempt to delete the document, as specified by the task id parsed into the parameter, from the collection by its ID. It can do so by specifying the ID in line 55 and MongoDB has deleted the document, we can redirect the user to GET / in line 56.

    Congratulations on making till this point! We just need to run the server. In our terminal, enter either node app.js or nodemon app.js .

    Right now, you should be able to see the completed version of our server rendered application. You should be able to Create, Read, Update and Delete your tasks as well.

  • Step 11: Troubleshooting Database Connections (Optional)

    Sometimes, you will not be able to connect to the database. This is because MongoDB will whitelist the IP Address that was used to create the database. As such, only the connection from that IP Address can be connected to the database.

    To whitelist your new IP Address, open up MongoDB Atlas Dashboard and select the Network Access that is shown on the side navigation panel.

    Click on the Add IP Address button. You will then need to enter your IP address in the Access List Entry field. Then, click on Confirm. You should then see your IP address added to the IP Access List. Restart your application and try connecting again.

    Do note that we highly discourage you from using the Allow Access from Anywhere as it is an unsafe security practice. This will allow anyone using the same db_connection string, from the .env file, to access the database.
